Strings KT
# Python String Functions - Complete Reference

---

## 1. Case Conversion Methods

### upper()
Converts all characters to uppercase.
```python
text = "hello world"
print(text.upper())  # HELLO WORLD
```

### lower()
Converts all characters to lowercase.
```python
text = "HELLO WORLD"
print(text.lower())  # hello world
```

### title()
Converts first character of each word to uppercase.
```python
text = "hello world python"
print(text.title())  # Hello World Python
```

### capitalize()
Converts first character of the string to uppercase.
```python
text = "hello world"
print(text.capitalize())  # Hello world
```

### swapcase()
Swaps uppercase to lowercase and vice versa.
```python
text = "Hello World"
print(text.swapcase())  # hELLO wORLD
```

### casefold()
Aggressive lowercase (handles special characters better than lower()).
```python
text = "HELLO StraC¬e"
print(text.casefold())  # hello strasse
```

---

## 2. Search and Find Methods

### find()
Returns the index of the first occurrence of a substring. Returns -1 if not found.
```python
text = "Hello World"
print(text.find("World"))  # 6
print(text.find("xyz"))    # -1
```

### rfind()
Returns the index of the last occurrence of a substring.
```python
text = "hello world hello"
print(text.rfind("hello"))  # 12
```

### index()
Same as find(), but raises ValueError if not found.
```python
text = "Hello World"
print(text.index("World"))  # 6
# text.index("xyz")  # ValueError!
```

### rindex()
Same as rfind(), but raises ValueError if not found.
```python
text = "hello world hello"
print(text.rindex("hello"))  # 12
```

### count()
Returns the number of occurrences of a substring.
```python
text = "hello world hello python hello"
print(text.count("hello"))  # 3
```

---

## 3. Validation/Check Methods (return True/False)

### startswith()
Checks if string starts with a specified prefix.
```python
text = "Hello World"
print(text.startswith("Hello"))  # True
print(text.startswith("World"))  # False
```

### endswith()
Checks if string ends with a specified suffix.
```python
text = "document.pdf"
print(text.endswith(".pdf"))   # True
print(text.endswith(".txt"))   # False
```

### isalpha()
Returns True if all characters are alphabetic.
```python
print("Hello".isalpha())    # True
print("Hello1".isalpha())   # False
print("Hello ".isalpha())   # False
```

### isdigit()
Returns True if all characters are digits.
```python
print("12345".isdigit())   # True
print("123.45".isdigit())  # False
```

### isnumeric()
Returns True if all characters are numeric (includes digits, fractions, etc.).
```python
print("12345".isnumeric())  # True
print("B=".isnumeric())      # True
print("12.5".isnumeric())   # False
```

### isdecimal()
Returns True if all characters are decimal characters.
```python
print("12345".isdecimal())  # True
print("B=".isdecimal())      # False
```

### isalnum()
Returns True if all characters are alphanumeric.
```python
print("Hello123".isalnum())   # True
print("Hello 123".isalnum())  # False
```

### isspace()
Returns True if all characters are whitespace.
```python
print("   ".isspace())      # True
print(" hello ".isspace())  # False
```

### islower()
Returns True if all cased characters are lowercase.
```python
print("hello".islower())   # True
print("Hello".islower())   # False
```

### isupper()
Returns True if all cased characters are uppercase.
```python
print("HELLO".isupper())   # True
print("Hello".isupper())   # False
```

### istitle()
Returns True if string is in title case.
```python
print("Hello World".istitle())  # True
print("Hello world".istitle())  # False
```

### isidentifier()
Returns True if string is a valid Python identifier.
```python
print("variable_name".isidentifier())  # True
print("2variable".isidentifier())      # False
```

### isprintable()
Returns True if all characters are printable.
```python
print("Hello".isprintable())    # True
print("Hello\n".isprintable())  # False
```

---

## 4. String Modification Methods

### replace()
Replaces occurrences of a substring with another.
```python
text = "Hello World"
print(text.replace("World", "Python"))  # Hello Python

# Replace only first n occurrences
text = "aaa bbb aaa"
print(text.replace("aaa", "ccc", 1))  # ccc bbb aaa
```

### strip()
Removes leading and trailing whitespace (or specified characters).
```python
text = "   Hello World   "
print(text.strip())       # "Hello World"

text = "***Hello***"
print(text.strip("*"))    # "Hello"
```

### lstrip()
Removes leading (left) whitespace or specified characters.
```python
text = "   Hello World   "
print(text.lstrip())  # "Hello World   "
```

### rstrip()
Removes trailing (right) whitespace or specified characters.
```python
text = "   Hello World   "
print(text.rstrip())  # "   Hello World"
```

### removeprefix() (Python 3.9+)
Removes a specific prefix from the string.
```python
text = "HelloWorld"
print(text.removeprefix("Hello"))  # World
```

### removesuffix() (Python 3.9+)
Removes a specific suffix from the string.
```python
text = "document.pdf"
print(text.removesuffix(".pdf"))  # document
```

---

## 5. Split and Join Methods

### split()
Splits string into a list using a delimiter.
```python
text = "Hello World Python"
print(text.split())        # ['Hello', 'World', 'Python']

csv = "apple,banana,cherry"
print(csv.split(","))      # ['apple', 'banana', 'cherry']

# Limit splits
text = "one-two-three-four"
print(text.split("-", 2))  # ['one', 'two', 'three-four']
```

### rsplit()
Splits from the right side.
```python
text = "one-two-three-four"
print(text.rsplit("-", 2))  # ['one-two', 'three', 'four']
```

### splitlines()
Splits string at line breaks.
```python
text = "Line1\nLine2\nLine3"
print(text.splitlines())  # ['Line1', 'Line2', 'Line3']
```

### join()
Joins elements of an iterable with the string as separator.
```python
words = ['Hello', 'World', 'Python']
print(" ".join(words))    # Hello World Python
print("-".join(words))    # Hello-World-Python
print(",".join(words))    # Hello,World,Python
```

### partition()
Splits string into 3 parts: before, separator, after (first occurrence).
```python
text = "Hello World Python"
print(text.partition("World"))  # ('Hello ', 'World', ' Python')
```

### rpartition()
Same as partition() but searches from the right.
```python
text = "Hello World World Python"
print(text.rpartition("World"))  # ('Hello World ', 'World', ' Python')
```

---

## 6. Padding and Alignment Methods

### center()
Centers the string within a specified width.
```python
text = "Hello"
print(text.center(20))       # "       Hello        "
print(text.center(20, "*"))  # "*******Hello********"
```

### ljust()
Left-justifies the string within a specified width.
```python
text = "Hello"
print(text.ljust(20))       # "Hello               "
print(text.ljust(20, "-"))  # "Hello---------------"
```

### rjust()
Right-justifies the string within a specified width.
```python
text = "Hello"
print(text.rjust(20))       # "               Hello"
print(text.rjust(20, "-"))  # "---------------Hello"
```

### zfill()
Pads string with zeros on the left to fill specified width.
```python
num = "42"
print(num.zfill(5))   # 00042

num = "-42"
print(num.zfill(5))   # -0042
```

---

## 7. Encoding and Translation Methods

### encode()
Encodes the string using the specified encoding.
```python
text = "Hello World"
print(text.encode("utf-8"))    # b'Hello World'
print(text.encode("ascii"))    # b'Hello World'
```

### maketrans() and translate()
Creates a translation table and applies it.
```python
# Replace characters
table = str.maketrans("aeiou", "12345")
text = "hello world"
print(text.translate(table))  # h2ll4 w4rld

# Remove characters
table = str.maketrans("", "", "aeiou")
text = "hello world"
print(text.translate(table))  # hll wrld
```

---

## 8. Formatting Methods

### format()
Formats the string with specified values.
```python
# Positional arguments
print("Hello, {}! You are {} years old.".format("Alice", 30))
# Hello, Alice! You are 30 years old.

# Named arguments
print("Hello, {name}! Age: {age}".format(name="Bob", age=25))
# Hello, Bob! Age: 25

# Number formatting
print("Price: {:.2f}".format(49.5))    # Price: 49.50
print("Percent: {:.1%}".format(0.85))  # Percent: 85.0%
```

### format_map()
Formats using a dictionary mapping.
```python
data = {"name": "Alice", "age": 30}
print("Name: {name}, Age: {age}".format_map(data))
# Name: Alice, Age: 30
```

### f-strings (Python 3.6+)
Inline string formatting (not a method, but essential).
```python
name = "Alice"
age = 30
print(f"Hello, {name}! You are {age} years old.")
# Hello, Alice! You are 30 years old.

# Expressions inside f-strings
print(f"Sum: {2 + 3}")          # Sum: 5
print(f"Upper: {name.upper()}")  # Upper: ALICE
```

---

## 9. Other Useful Methods

### expandtabs()
Sets the tab size for tab characters.
```python
text = "Hello\tWorld\tPython"
print(text.expandtabs(4))   # Hello   World   Python
print(text.expandtabs(10))  # Hello     World     Python
```

---

## 10. Built-in Functions for Strings

### len()
Returns the length of the string.
```python
text = "Hello World"
print(len(text))  # 11
```

### ord()
Returns the Unicode code point of a character.
```python
print(ord("A"))  # 65
print(ord("a"))  # 97
```

### chr()
Returns the character for a Unicode code point.
```python
print(chr(65))   # A
print(chr(97))   # a
```

### str()
Converts an object to its string representation.
```python
print(str(123))      # "123"
print(str(3.14))     # "3.14"
print(str([1,2,3]))  # "[1, 2, 3]"
```

### repr()
Returns a printable representation of the object.
```python
text = "Hello\nWorld"
print(repr(text))  # 'Hello\nWorld'
```

### sorted()
Returns a sorted list of characters.
```python
text = "python"
print(sorted(text))  # ['h', 'n', 'o', 'p', 't', 'y']
```

### reversed()
Returns a reversed iterator.
```python
text = "Hello"
print("".join(reversed(text)))  # olleH
```

---

## 11. String Slicing (Not a method, but essential)

```python
text = "Hello World"

print(text[0])       # H (first character)
print(text[-1])      # d (last character)
print(text[0:5])     # Hello (index 0 to 4)
print(text[6:])      # World (index 6 to end)
print(text[:5])      # Hello (start to index 4)
print(text[::2])     # HloWrd (every 2nd character)
print(text[::-1])    # dlroW olleH (reverse string)
```

---

## 12. String Concatenation and Repetition

```python
# Concatenation
str1 = "Hello"
str2 = "World"
print(str1 + " " + str2)  # Hello World

# Repetition
print("Ha" * 3)  # HaHaHa

# Join (preferred for multiple strings)
parts = ["Hello", "World", "Python"]
print(" ".join(parts))  # Hello World Python
```

